1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,640
Stan has one big thing due tomorrow.

2
00:00:02,640 --> 00:00:06,000
So tonight, he sits down to finally start it.

3
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:09,680
And then, somehow, the kitchen really needs cleaning.

4
00:00:09,680 --> 00:00:12,160
His desk needs reorganizing.

5
00:00:12,160 --> 00:00:14,760
He should probably reply to that email first.

6
00:00:14,760 --> 00:00:18,080
He watches one video, just one.

7
00:00:18,080 --> 00:00:21,920
The whole night, Stan is busy, Stan is moving,

8
00:00:21,920 --> 00:00:25,720
and Stan does not touch the one thing he actually has to do.

9
00:00:25,720 --> 00:00:28,480
And he feels terrible the entire time.

10
00:00:28,480 --> 00:00:30,720
Now, here's the giveaway.

11
00:00:30,720 --> 00:00:33,040
Stan is not being lazy.

12
00:00:33,040 --> 00:00:35,400
A lazy person would be relaxed.

13
00:00:35,400 --> 00:00:37,560
Stan is suffering.

14
00:00:37,560 --> 00:00:39,640
So what is actually going on?

15
00:00:39,640 --> 00:00:42,520
Because procrastination is not laziness.

16
00:00:42,520 --> 00:00:44,040
It is not bad planning.

17
00:00:44,040 --> 00:00:46,120
And the ancient Greeks were so obsessed with it

18
00:00:46,120 --> 00:00:48,040
that they gave it its own name.

19
00:00:48,040 --> 00:00:51,240
We are taught that procrastination is basically laziness

20
00:00:51,240 --> 00:00:53,680
or being bad with time.

21
00:00:53,680 --> 00:00:56,960
So the fix we are handed is always the same.

22
00:00:56,960 --> 00:01:00,320
Try harder, get a planner, have more discipline,

23
00:01:00,320 --> 00:01:02,240
and that advice almost never works.

24
00:01:02,240 --> 00:01:03,680
There is a reason for that.

25
00:01:03,680 --> 00:01:06,440
It is aimed at the wrong problem entirely.

26
00:01:06,440 --> 00:01:10,160
Because procrastination has almost nothing to do with time.

27
00:01:10,160 --> 00:01:11,800
It has to do with feeling.

28
00:01:11,800 --> 00:01:13,360
When you sit down to face a task,

29
00:01:13,360 --> 00:01:15,840
your brain does not just see the task.

30
00:01:15,840 --> 00:01:17,680
It feels something about it.

31
00:01:17,680 --> 00:01:21,880
Maybe boredom, maybe anxiety, maybe a quiet fear

32
00:01:21,880 --> 00:01:25,080
that you will try, and it still will not be good enough.

33
00:01:25,080 --> 00:01:27,840
And your brain, more than almost anything,

34
00:01:27,840 --> 00:01:30,280
wants that bad feeling to stop right now.

35
00:01:30,280 --> 00:01:33,360
So it reaches for the one move that kills it instantly.

36
00:01:33,360 --> 00:01:35,120
It avoids the task.

37
00:01:35,120 --> 00:01:37,240
That is all procrastination is.

38
00:01:37,240 --> 00:01:40,080
Not laziness, mood repair,

39
00:01:40,080 --> 00:01:42,000
a quick hit of relief in the present,

40
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:45,240
put on a credit card that your future self has to pay.

41
00:01:45,240 --> 00:01:47,440
And this is exactly why procrastination

42
00:01:47,440 --> 00:01:50,280
is basically the opposite of laziness.

43
00:01:50,280 --> 00:01:51,840
Lazy is comfortable.

44
00:01:51,840 --> 00:01:53,920
Lazy is fine doing nothing.

45
00:01:53,960 --> 00:01:57,040
But a procrastinator desperately wants to do the thing,

46
00:01:57,040 --> 00:01:58,680
fully intends to,

47
00:01:58,680 --> 00:02:00,600
swears they will start in five minutes

48
00:02:00,600 --> 00:02:03,560
and feels awful the whole time they do not.

49
00:02:03,560 --> 00:02:05,440
There's nothing relaxed about it.

50
00:02:05,440 --> 00:02:07,920
And there is a cruel little twist baked in.

51
00:02:07,920 --> 00:02:10,520
The one who pays the bill is future you.

52
00:02:10,520 --> 00:02:14,160
And your brain treats future you almost like a stranger.

53
00:02:14,160 --> 00:02:17,240
Present you grabs the relief.

54
00:02:17,240 --> 00:02:20,480
Future you is the one panicking at two in the morning.

55
00:02:20,480 --> 00:02:22,400
And here is the strangest part.

56
00:02:22,400 --> 00:02:24,720
The people who procrastinate the most

57
00:02:24,720 --> 00:02:27,040
are often the ones who care the most.

58
00:02:27,040 --> 00:02:29,880
Because if you are terrified of doing it badly,

59
00:02:29,880 --> 00:02:31,920
the bad feeling is even bigger.

60
00:02:31,920 --> 00:02:34,080
So you flinch away even harder.

61
00:02:34,080 --> 00:02:36,560
Now, if you think this is a modern problem,

62
00:02:36,560 --> 00:02:38,600
something phones and streaming did to us,

63
00:02:38,600 --> 00:02:40,560
the ancient Greeks would laugh.

64
00:02:40,560 --> 00:02:43,160
They were fascinated by this exact puzzle.

65
00:02:43,160 --> 00:02:46,560
Thousands of years ago, they even had a word for it.

66
00:02:46,560 --> 00:02:48,080
Akrasia.

67
00:02:48,080 --> 00:02:51,400
It means doing something even while you know fully

68
00:02:51,400 --> 00:02:54,560
that it goes against your better judgment.

69
00:02:54,560 --> 00:02:56,760
Socrates and Aristotle genuinely argued

70
00:02:56,760 --> 00:02:59,000
about how it is even possible.

71
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:03,120
How can a person know the smart thing to do, truly know it,

72
00:03:03,120 --> 00:03:04,800
and still not do it?

73
00:03:04,800 --> 00:03:07,400
Procrastination is not a bug of the modern world.

74
00:03:07,400 --> 00:03:10,200
It is one of the oldest riddles of being human.

75
00:03:10,200 --> 00:03:14,680
And the word we use is a tiny confession all on its own.

76
00:03:14,680 --> 00:03:18,920
Procrastinate comes from Latin, pro, meaning forward,

77
00:03:18,920 --> 00:03:21,840
and cras, meaning tomorrow.

78
00:03:21,840 --> 00:03:23,760
Put them together, and it literally

79
00:03:23,760 --> 00:03:26,160
means to put it forward to tomorrow.

80
00:03:26,160 --> 00:03:30,000
Humans have been doing this so reliably for so long

81
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:33,520
that we built a word for it out of the actual word for tomorrow.

82
00:03:33,520 --> 00:03:36,000
So here's the part that turns everything

83
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:38,040
you have been told upside down.

84
00:03:38,040 --> 00:03:41,320
Because procrastination runs on bad feelings,

85
00:03:41,320 --> 00:03:44,320
the way most of us fight it actually feeds it.

86
00:03:44,320 --> 00:03:48,200
You put the thing off, then you call yourself lazy and useless

87
00:03:48,200 --> 00:03:50,360
and ask what is wrong with you.

88
00:03:50,360 --> 00:03:52,640
And now there is a whole new layer of bad feeling

89
00:03:52,640 --> 00:03:53,960
stuck to that task.

90
00:03:53,960 --> 00:03:55,960
So the next time you go to start it,

91
00:03:55,960 --> 00:03:59,680
there is even more to flinch away from.

92
00:03:59,680 --> 00:04:01,480
Guilt is not the cure.

93
00:04:01,480 --> 00:04:03,280
Guilt is the fuel.

94
00:04:03,280 --> 00:04:06,360
The harder you beat yourself up, the bigger and scarier

95
00:04:06,360 --> 00:04:08,080
the thing becomes.

96
00:04:08,080 --> 00:04:10,120
Which leads to the most backward sounding

97
00:04:10,120 --> 00:04:11,680
fix in all of psychology.

98
00:04:11,680 --> 00:04:14,000
And it is a real study.

99
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:16,920
Researchers track students across their exams.

100
00:04:16,960 --> 00:04:19,160
The students who simply forgave themselves

101
00:04:19,160 --> 00:04:21,960
for procrastinating before the first exam

102
00:04:21,960 --> 00:04:25,520
went on to procrastinate less before the next one.

103
00:04:25,520 --> 00:04:27,680
Not the most disciplined students,

104
00:04:27,680 --> 00:04:29,040
the most forgiving ones.

105
00:04:29,040 --> 00:04:31,440
Because once you drop the guilt,

106
00:04:31,440 --> 00:04:33,880
the task stops radiating dread

107
00:04:33,880 --> 00:04:37,480
and it quietly turns back into just a task.

108
00:04:37,480 --> 00:04:40,360
The secret was never to be harder on yourself.

109
00:04:40,360 --> 00:04:43,960
It was to stop making the thing feel so awful to walk up to

110
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:45,520
and then to shrink it.

111
00:04:45,520 --> 00:04:47,160
Not write the essay.

112
00:04:47,160 --> 00:04:49,040
Write one bad sentence.

113
00:04:49,040 --> 00:04:51,960
Make the first step too small to be scary.

114
00:04:51,960 --> 00:04:53,720
So the next time you are Stan,

115
00:04:53,720 --> 00:04:55,400
scrubbing a perfectly clean kitchen

116
00:04:55,400 --> 00:04:57,840
to avoid the thing you swore you would do,

117
00:04:57,840 --> 00:04:59,400
do not reach for the guilt.

118
00:04:59,400 --> 00:05:02,320
That is the trap that keeps the whole loop spinning.

119
00:05:02,320 --> 00:05:05,640
You are not lazy and you are not broken.

120
00:05:05,640 --> 00:05:07,480
You are doing one of the most human things

121
00:05:07,480 --> 00:05:10,280
there is, quietly trading a little peace now

122
00:05:10,280 --> 00:05:12,120
for a little panic later.

123
00:05:12,160 --> 00:05:14,320
The Greeks never did solve it,

124
00:05:14,320 --> 00:05:15,840
but they understood it.

125
00:05:15,840 --> 00:05:17,880
And it turns out that understanding it

126
00:05:17,880 --> 00:05:20,040
and going a little easier on yourself

127
00:05:20,040 --> 00:05:22,920
is the closest thing we have ever found to a cure.
